You can get the size of a string in C++ using the `size()` or `length()` member functions of the `std::string` class. Here is an example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string myString = "Hello, World!";

    std::cout << "Length of the string: " << myString.size() << std::endl;
    // Alternatively, you can also use:
    // std::cout << "Length of the string: " << myString.length() << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

To get the size of a string in C++, you can use the `size()` function provided by the `std::string` class. Here is an example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string str = "Hello, World!";

    std::cout << "Size of the string: " << str.size() << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This will output the size of the string `str` which in this case is the number of characters in the string "Hello, World!" the output will be:

```
Size of the string: 13
